# Memory Bank

The agent's memory resets completely between sessions. `memory-bank/` is the **only** persistent link to previous work in this repository — it must be read at the start of every task and maintained with precision.

**I MUST read ALL core memory bank files at the start of EVERY task — this is not optional.**

## Structure

Files build on each other in a clear hierarchy:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    PB[projectbrief.md] --> PC[productContext.md]
    PB --> SP[systemPatterns.md]
    PB --> TC[techContext.md]

    PC --> AC[activeContext.md]
    SP --> AC
    TC --> AC

    AC --> P[progress.md]
    AC --> T[tasks/]
```

### Core files (required, in `memory-bank/`)

1. **`projectbrief.md`** — foundation document; core requirements and goals; source of truth for project scope.
2. **`productContext.md`** — why this project exists, problems it solves, how it should work, UX goals.
3. **`systemPatterns.md`** — system architecture, key technical decisions (ADRs D1–…), design patterns, component boundaries.
4. **`techContext.md`** — technologies, development setup, technical constraints, dependencies.
5. **`activeContext.md`** — current work focus, recent changes, next steps, active decisions, open questions/risks.
6. **`progress.md`** — what works, what's left to build, current status, known issues.

### Task tracking (required, in `memory-bank/tasks/`)

All implementation work is tracked in **task folders** under `memory-bank/tasks/` — structure, protocol and lifecycle are defined in:

- `task-folder-workflow.mdc` — folder structure, mandatory files (TASK/PLAN/WORKLOG/HANDOFF), status protocol;
- `task-index-workflow.mdc` — keeping `tasks/INDEX.md` in sync;
- `task-quality-lifecycle.mdc` — docs/tests/commit/verification per task;
- `memory-task-minor-version-bump.mdc` — version bump on task completion.

### Additional context

Create additional files/folders inside `memory-bank/` when they help organize complex feature docs, integration specs, testing strategies or deployment procedures.

## Core workflows

### Start of any task (Plan or Act)

1. Read **all** core memory bank files (1–6 above).
2. Check `memory-bank/tasks/INDEX.md` and the relevant task folder.
3. If files are incomplete or contradict the code — the code is the source of truth; record the mismatch and fix the documentation as part of the task.
4. Only then plan or implement.

### During and after work

1. Execute within the task protocol (see task rules above).
2. Update `activeContext.md` (focus, decisions, recent changes) and `progress.md` (status) after significant changes.
3. Respect `documentation-separation.mdc`: memory-bank is **internal agent documentation**; human-facing docs live in `README.md` + `docs/` and never reference memory-bank.

## Documentation updates

Memory Bank updates occur when:

1. Discovering new project patterns.
2. After implementing significant changes.
3. When the user requests **"update memory bank"** — then I MUST review **every** memory bank file, even those not requiring updates; focus on `activeContext.md` and `progress.md`.
4. When context needs clarification.

## Project intelligence

Durable, project-specific insights (implementation paths, user preferences, known challenges, evolution of decisions) are captured as rules in `.cursor/rules/` of this repository — validate patterns with the user before writing them down.

REMEMBER: after every memory reset, the agent begins completely fresh. The Memory Bank must be maintained as if the agent's effectiveness depends entirely on its accuracy — because it does.
